Part 11

The telegram from Odisha was delivered to the Nandyal administrative office on a Tuesday afternoon.

It had only four words.

*Binay serious. Come home.*

Suresh had brought it in, his boots making a hurried, squeaking sound on the linoleum.

Vikram didn't read it twice.

He stood up from his brown leatherette chair.

"Pack the files, Suresh," he said.

"And the chair, sir? Should we send it by truck to the railway station?"

Vikram looked at the cracked armrest where the black tape had started peeling to show the grey foam inside.

"No," Vikram said.

"Leave it here. Let someone else sit in it."

He took his small leather bag, the same suitcase he'd brought five years ago, and walked out to the waiting car.

---

The Odisha house was silent.

Binay was in the upstairs bedroom, the one that looked out over the kitchen garden.

He was propped up on two flat pillows, his breathing shallow, the yellow jaundice showing deep in the whites of his eyes.

Rohan was sitting on the wooden stool near the window.

His shoes were clean today, but he had his hands in his pockets, his shoulders hunched as he watched Vikram enter.

He didn't stand up.

"You took your time," Rohan said.

"The train was delayed at Khurda," Vikram said.

He sat on the edge of the bed.

Binay's hand was dry and cold. The skin felt like loose parchment, the veins rising blue and stiff against the bone.

He opened his eyes slowly.

He looked at Vikram. Then at Rohan near the window.

"The Nandyal plant," Binay whispered.

"It is running, Papa," Vikram said. "The bottling unit is complete."

Binay nodded once, his eyelids closing again.

"Rohan," he said, his voice dry.

Rohan stood up, but he didn't come to the bed. He stayed near the cupboard.

"Yes, Papa."

"The company... it is yours now. Both of you."

Rohan looked at the floor.

"Vikram runs the board, Papa. I am just a site engineer."

Binay didn't answer.

He had already gone back to that quiet, unmoving state where the words of his sons didn't reach him.

Vikram stood up.

He walked to the window.

Rohan was looking at the kitchen garden where Ramu was collecting dry leaves in a basket.

"You should have stayed at the head office," Rohan said, his voice low. "Reddy says you did all the work in the South. He says the board only wants your signature."

"The signature is just ink, Rohan," Vikram said.

"It is not," Rohan said, turning his back.

"It is what decides whose name goes on the gate."

He walked out of the room.

His footsteps were loud on the wooden stairs, fading until only the slow, heavy breathing of their father remained in the room.

Vikram sat back on the edge of the bed.

He held the old man's hand.

The room smelled of barley water and the spirit the nurse used for the thermometer.

Outside, the sun was setting behind the kitchen garden, casting the shadow of the neem trees long and dark over the compost pit.

He knew this was the last week.

He knew the white coat was gone, and the company was all that remained.

But as he held his father's cold hand in the dark room, the fourteen hundred crore felt like nothing but a number written on a wall that was about to fall down.

